metadata.name: Parametric Decoy #86
metadata.description:
The project started with the discovery of an unusual shape. Draw two parallel sine arcs and connect their opposite points. That's how you get one slice of Parametric Decoy. The shape may appear in its different phases. Sometimes elegant, sometimes awkward. Sometimes broken, sometimes symmetrical. Only connectivity stays the same.

Features:
- size: small, medium, large
- color: *several options*
- background: transparent, halftone, cutout
- distorted: no, maybe*, twisted, displaced, yes**

* "maybe" means I'm not quite sure if distortion affects visible part of the shape
** "yes" means combination of "twisted" and "displaced"

Press S to save. To download in custom size (ex. 2000px width), add &size=2000 to url, reload and press S.

Made with p5js, inspired by pop-art collages and my own geometric sketches

metadata.name: inlim:in #228
metadata.description:
"inlim:in" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at PARIS+ par Art Basel

Atemporal iridescent fragments of the in between. The series is inspired by the many liminal spaces and unseen influences that permeate the visible universe and its participants. Created with GLSL, every piece of the series is generated using the space around the visible object to cast its shape. The series creates a gentle and colorful expanse through which viewers might contemplate what it is to exist at an infinite threshold.

metadata.name: pantonX.3 #139
metadata.description:
pantonX.3
is the third drop of the zukuNFT project, which is dedicated to geometric and minimalist standards of early geometric art.
inspired by the "bauhaus grundkurs" based on the didactic concepts of the bauhaus (1919-1933) and its teachings by johannes itten, paul klee, wassily kandinsky, lászló moholy-nagy and josef albers. the preliminary courses and their basic design tasks dealt syntactically with circle, line and square as well as color, and contrasts.

i am a visual artist and have worked in the field of coding since the early years of processing.
always loved geometric and minimalist art, bauhaus, de stijl, piet mondrian, sol leWitt -- just to name a few -- and last but not least verner panton, have had a influence on my artistic work.

metadata.name: Provence #464
metadata.description:
The south of France namely the Provence has a cultural history of being an inspiration for impressionists and post-impressionists in the past.
For me personally the Provence is the place i was spending long, peaceful holidays as a child within beautiful nature.
This work does not so much aim for being realistic, rather than give an impression or feeling for this wonderful landscape. 
There are just a few different elements and concepts and yet there is variety of fascinating results.
I really hope you will enjoy your minting.

Notes:
STARTUP AND RENDERING MAY TAKE SOME TIME. (Up to 1min)
Code was written in typescript.
The only used libraries were chroma.js and simplex-noise

metadata.name: BINARY WORDS #102
metadata.description:
I drew my first 8x8 pixel binary image on 11/08/2022 with 'iloveyou' encoded for my wife, it was our 10-year anniversary on this day.  After that made this generative stuff for fxhash's birthday bash.

#fxhashturnsone

Donations:
25% to ThreeJs team

The image contains a binary coded word or phrase with a length of 8 characters. The grays represents 0, the other colors represents 1. One row -> one character. Should be proceed decoding from left to right and from top to bottom.

An example: 'iloveyou'

01101001
01101100
01101111
01110110
01100101
01111001
01101111
01110101

The fxrandom selects a word and the program converts it to binary data. After that, the background (ground and sky) is randomly generated from color schemes. Then the binary gray colors are drawn. Also the color of light next to null colors is randomly generated from color schemes. Random affects also the animation.

The animation stops when you do these interactions below, then restarts after a few seconds of inactivity.

Press spacebar to change:

- frame view -> without frame
- without frame -> original 8x8px size
- original 8x8px size -> frame view

Press 's' to save an svg from current view.

Notes:
- Build with ReactJs and TweenJs
- Every upcoming day, half of the remaining pieces are burned.

Happy Birthday fxhash community!
I'm glad to be among you!

metadata.name: Trust #209
metadata.description:
Trust is an abstraction of the creative process, finding the line just before form becomes texture. Your experience with the painting requires trust; trust that something will appear from the chaos of the empty space, trust that the composition you imagine halfway through will evolve along with your ideas, and trust that the etchings lend a helping hand to the message of the piece. You may find yourself pulled left and right when decisions are made, and your interpretation at 25%, 50%, and 90% will all differ. This is what makes creating so fulfilling to me, a work of art can change course wildly from start to finish, ever molding itself until it enters the kiln.

Press ‘1’, ‘2’, or  ‘3’ to increase resolution (default is 1, higher than default may not work on certain browsers. Successfully testing in Chrome, Brave, and Opera GX with hardware acceleration enabled)

Click or tap to zoom to full res (exact zoom depends on your display)
Press ’s’ to save a .png
Press ’t’ to toggle brush texture

Created with p5.js and chroma.js

metadata.name: Magic Board #93
metadata.description:
When the ratio of two quantities is equal to the ratio of their sum to the larger quantity, there is a golden ratio in geometric patterns, and this property can create different geometric shapes.
The points are all randomly placed in each design, and the placement of these shapes together creates the impression of a geometric pattern based on random processing.
There is no end to these geometric patterns.
press 's' to save original size

metadata.name: Improvisation I #174
metadata.description:
“Improvisation I“ was born after my experiments with Fractal Brownian Motion. 

During random tweaks of colours, parameters and sizes I got something that really clicked with me — a picture I wanted to get out of the code some time ago. 

Painterly looking curves and blots with subtle colours transitions create a calming picture, sometimes resembling outlines of a landscape.

——————

To change the size of an image, open it in live view and add ‘&size=[size (6800 max.)]’ to the end of the URL. 
Press [C] to load a clean version without grain.
Press [S] to save the image.

Created using p5.js and GLSL.
License: CC BY-NC-SA 4.0.

——————

hrunz. — Oct. 2022.
